The defeat of the Town in these early times has however probably proved its salvation. Had the ultimate victory rested with the City, the University would doubtless have ceased to exist3 the irrespon- sible bands ol scholars and teachers would have migrated to some other spot. There were as yet no public buildings, no colleges no special advantages lor study at Oxford, to cause them to hesitate. The city apart from the University would in six centuries have lost its mediaeval importance, and degenerated into a decayed country market town ; a testing place
